example.p:
We will prove the binomial theorem using mathematical induction; that is, (a + b)^n = \sum_{k = 0}^{n} \binom{n}{k} a^k b^{n - k}, where a and b are real numbers, n \in \mathbb{N}, and \binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k! (n - k)!} is the binomial coefficient.  We first show that \binom{n + 1}{k} = \binom{n}{k} + \binom{n}{k - 1}. This result follows from
                \binom{n}{k} + \binom{n}{k - 1} & = \frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!} +\frac{n!}{(k-1)!(n - k + 1)!}
                & = \frac{(n + 1)!}{k!(n + 1 - k)!}
                & =\binom{n + 1}{k}
            .
                n!
                n factorial

                \binom{n}{k}
                binomial coefficient n!/(k!(n-k)!)
